#
Assignment: Grammy Record of the Year Winners & Nominees





Introduction

Every year since 1959 a Grammy Award has been presented by National Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences for Record of the Year. This award is intended to "honor artistic achievement, technical proficiency and overall excellence in the recording industry, without regard to sales or chart position" [Source: http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy]. Essentially, Record of the Year recognises an individual song performance by an artist or group of artists. It is judged on the performance (and latterly production, engineering and mixing) merits, not its lyrics or composition.

Some well known artists (e.g. The Beatles, U2, Adele and Celine Dion) have won or been nominated; likewise, there are a number of famous artists that have never been nominated (e.g. The Beach Boys, The Rolling Stones).

Is there anything special about these nominated and winning records? Do they have certain characteristics or special features that set them apart from their peers? Can we explain why Frank Sinatra has been nominated seven times but Bob Marley has not been nominated at all? Are these nominees commercially successful? Or is a record more likely to win if it is considered "commercially successful"? Essentially - what "makes" a Grammy Nominated Record of the Year?

This analysis attempts to answer some of these questions by using data sourced from web-scraping, static datasets and by using The EchoNest API.

#2. Obtaining the Raw Data

In order to consider our questions further, we need to obtain raw data that will allow for further analysis and hopefully provide some insights.

Firstly, we need to ascertain the Record of the Year winner and nominees for each year since 1959 as this will form the basis for our further data collection.

#Web Scraping - Wikipedia Table

Wikipedia helpfully provides a table that we can scrape into our iPython notebook. The raw format of this can be seen below:

In [3]: 
HTML('<iframe src=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Record_of_the_Year#Recipients width=1050 height=500></iframe>')
Out[3]:

One way we can scrape this data is by by creating a csv file and writing column titles to it in preparation for the addition of the Wikipedia data. We can then scrape the Wikipedia page. As the formatting of the html code used for the Wikipedia page makes it difficult to read, we can also pass the page to BeautifulSoup in order to make better sense of the results:

In [3]: 
import csv

gfile = open("grammys.csv", "wb")
win = csv.writer(gfile)
win.writerow(["Year","Winner_raw","Work_raw","Nominees_raw"])
url = "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Record_of_the_Year" 
rq = requests.get(url)
soup = BeautifulSoup(rq.content)
nomswins = soup.find_all("table", class_="wikitable sortable")

print nomswins

Once the data has been scraped we can then put this into the applicable variables (columns) within the csv file.

We want to ignore the header row, then allot each subset of data within the table into the appropriate variable. We can also ask that this be encoded as utf-8, so special characters such as and * are preserved:

In [4]: 
complete_list = []
for table in nomswins:
    trs = table.find_all("tr")[1:] 
    for tr in trs:
        tds = tr.find_all("td")
        ths = tr.find_all("th")
        firstwk = tds[1].find("a") 
        Year = ths[0].get_text().encode("utf-8")
        Winner_raw = tds[0].get_text().encode("utf-8")
        Work_raw = firstwk.get_text().encode("utf-8")
        Nominees_raw = tds[2].get_text().encode("utf-8")
        win.writerow([Year, Winner_raw, Work_raw, Nominees_raw])
      
gfile.close()

The newly created csv file can now be read into the notebook; this gives us our first look at the data:

In [5]: 
grammys = pd.read_csv("grammys.csv")
grammys.head()

Some of the data, such as that within the "Year" and "Work_raw" variables appears at first glance to be relatively clean. It it immediately clear that the data within the other two variables requires cleaning.

If we take a closer look at the "Winner_raw" data, we can see that this varies depending on the year of the award. Initially, the artist was the sole winner of the award. Then, it was decided that producers should be acknowledged and in later years the engineers and then sound mixers were also included in the award. This can be seen below:

In [6]: 
grammys.Winner_raw.values

For consistency, we will retain the name of the artist only and remove the other information for each object. We can do this by splitting each object along its natural break - '':

In [7]: 
grammys['Winner_raw'] = grammys['Winner_raw'].str.split('\n').str[0]

Some of the winners, such as groups like 'U2' and 'Green Day' or individual artists (e.g. 'Adele') do not require further cleaning. However, cleaning the remainder will require the definition and then application of a function. We can see that the remaining dirty data has a consistent theme. It is separated by a comma with the first winner's surname, then the winner's first names are duplicated and joined. We can define a function to treat this as follows:

In [10]: 
def func(badnames):
    
    if ',' in badnames:
        fix = badnames.split(' ')
        art = fix[1][int(len(fix[1])/2):] + ' '
        fix.remove(fix[0])
        fix.remove(fix[0])
        for i in fix:
            art += str(i) + ' '
        return art

The above function ignores each group in the winner variable. When applied, it only looks at objects where a ',' is present. In the case of 'Winehouse, AmyAmy Winehouse', the function recognises the presence of ',' and then splits this object into sub-objects separated by a space (' ') - so 'Winehouse,' 'AmyAmy' & 'Winehouse'.

The function then takes the second sub-object - in this case 'AmyAmy', divides it in half then adds a space, thus creating 'Amy Amy'. Combined with the other sub-objects this creates 'Winehouse, Amy Amy Winehouse'. The function then removes the first sub-object - 'Winehouse,' then the next sub-object - 'Amy', creating 'Amy Winehouse' which is the intended outcome.

We can then create a new variable called 'Winner1', apply the function to the 'Winner_raw' variable and fill our new variable with the results:

In [11]: 
grammys.insert(2, 'Winner1', '')
grammys['Winner1'] = grammys['Winner_raw'].apply(func)  
grammys

Our new variable, 'Winner 1', has some 'None' results. This is because we only asked the function to look at the dirty data. We can now define a new, more simple function and a variable called 'Winner' for the final winner information.

The function below looks at the data in 'Winner1'. If this equals 'None', then it takes the corresponding data in 'Winner_raw' and places it into our new 'Winner' variable. If there is data in 'Winner1' then this is placed into the 'Winner' variable:

In [12]: 
def func1(art):
    if art['Winner1'] == None:
        return art['Winner_raw']
    elif art['Winner1'] != None:
        return art['Winner1']
    
grammys.insert(1, 'Winner', '')
grammys['Winner'] = grammys.apply(func1, axis=1)
grammys

grammys.rename(columns={'Work_raw': 'Work'}, inplace=True)

Now we can write the semi-cleaned data to our 'grammys' csv file. This creates a checkpoint and allows us to the data clean further. If any mistakes are made, we only need to revert back to this point and not re-run every code item above. In particular, this ensures that we are not repetitively (and needlessly) scraping and re-scraping the Wikipedia page:

In [17]: 
grammys.to_csv("grammys.csv", index=False)

Now, we re-read in the data:

In [18]: 
grammys = pd.read_csv("grammys.csv")

In each award year there are five nominees in total. We have one on the nominees split into the 'Winner' and 'Work' category. We now need to split each of the losing nominees and their work into their own row and separate variables and further clean the data.

We can start by splitting each of the objects in the 'Nominees_raw' variable into its own column by asking to split the strings:

In [20]: 
grammys['Nominees_raw1'] = grammys['Nominees_raw'].str.split('\r\n"').str[1]
grammys['Nominees_raw2'] = grammys['Nominees_raw'].str.split('\r\n"').str[2]
grammys['Nominees_raw3'] = grammys['Nominees_raw'].str.split('\r\n"').str[3]
grammys['Nominees_raw4'] = grammys['Nominees_raw'].str.split('\r\n"').str[4]
grammys.head()

This has now moved each of the losing nominees and their work into its own variable.

We now need to create new sub-variables for each losing nominee, splitting out the artist and work details into separate variables:

In [21]: 
grammys['Nominees_work1'] = grammys['Nominees_raw1'].str.split('" by ').str[0]
grammys['Nominees_art1'] = grammys['Nominees_raw1'].str.split('" by ').str[1]
grammys['Nominees_work2'] = grammys['Nominees_raw2'].str.split('" by ').str[0]
grammys['Nominees_art2'] = grammys['Nominees_raw2'].str.split('" by ').str[1]
grammys['Nominees_work3'] = grammys['Nominees_raw3'].str.split('" by ').str[0]
grammys['Nominees_art3'] = grammys['Nominees_raw3'].str.split('" by ').str[1]
grammys['Nominees_work4'] = grammys['Nominees_raw4'].str.split('" by ').str[0]
grammys['Nominees_art4'] = grammys['Nominees_raw4'].str.split('" by ').str[1]

Now, we want each nominee to have their own row. This will allow us to append future data about theh artist and work on its own individual row. We can do this by assigning the year of nomination to each of the losing nominees and their work in an individual dataframe for each of the nominee groupings (i.e. 1, 2, 3 and 4):

In [29]: 
nom1 = pd.DataFrame(grammys, columns=['Year', 'Nominees_work1', 'Nominees_art1'])
nom2 = pd.DataFrame(grammys, columns=['Year', 'Nominees_work2', 'Nominees_art2'])
nom3 = pd.DataFrame(grammys, columns=['Year', 'Nominees_work3', 'Nominees_art3'])
nom4 = pd.DataFrame(grammys, columns=['Year', 'Nominees_work4', 'Nominees_art4'])

We can now rename each variable so it matches the variables housing our cleaned winner data:

In [30]: 
nom1.rename(columns={'Nominees_work1': 'Work', 'Nominees_art1': 'Artist'}, inplace=True)
nom2.rename(columns={'Nominees_work2': 'Work', 'Nominees_art2': 'Artist'}, inplace=True)
nom3.rename(columns={'Nominees_work3': 'Work', 'Nominees_art3': 'Artist'}, inplace=True)
nom4.rename(columns={'Nominees_work4': 'Work', 'Nominees_art4': 'Artist'}, inplace=True)

Then, we concatenate the four nominee dataframes together into a new dataframe called "nominees". To 'future proof' this new dataframe we can ignore the index; this assigns each entry its own individual index and then allows for additional data to be appended to each work during the latter stages of our data gathering and cleaning:

In [31]: 
nominees = pd.concat((nom1, nom2, nom3, nom4), ignore_index=True)
In [32]: 
nominees.sort_index(by='Year')

We now see that each of the losing nominees has their own row containing the year of nomination, the artist name and their work.

However, we need some way of noting whether the nominee was a winner that year or not. We can do this by inserting a new variable entitled 'Winner' and filling this with 'None' values to signify that they did not win:

In [33]: 
nominees.insert(3, 'Winner', None)
nominees

Now we can turn our attention to our winners for each year. We can create a dataframe called 'winners':

In [34]: 
winners = pd.DataFrame(grammys, columns=['Year', 'Work', 'Winner'])

In some instances, splitting columns can leave instances of invisible whitespace at the end of each string. To ensure that there are no issues during the analysis stage, we can strip out any whitespace at the end of each string prior to saving the dataset:

In [40]: 
grammys['Artist'] = grammys['Artist'].map(str.strip)
grammys['Work'] = grammys['Work'].map(str.strip)

#Static Dataset - The Britburn Project

The Britburn Project is a labour of love by a number of music buffs. They wanted to 'create a library of every charting U.K. track, including B-sides, labels, lyrics and other memorabilia'. Their work has been fact-checked and made available to the public to download as an Excel file:

In [5]: 
HTML('<iframe src=http://www.britburn.co.uk/ width=1050 height=500></iframe>')
Out[5]:

The Excel file is reasonably large and contains a number of tabbed sheets. As we are only interested in individual songs - and not albums or sheet music - an amended Excel file entitled 'Britburn_raw.xls' has been appended to this report in order to reduce the size of the files. We can now read in this raw set of spreadsheets as individual dataframes. The first sheet contains details of every UK charting (i.e. Top 100) work between 01 January 1952 and 31 December 1989:

In [42]: 
britburnmain = pd.read_excel("Britburn_raw.xls", "Britburn")
britburnmain.head()
Out[42]:

We can now read this to a new Excel file. As we are going to remove a substantial amount of data and may require this in future a checkpoint is created. We can always revisit the combined data and extract further information from it if need be:

In [47]: 
britburnall.to_excel("britburn.xls", index=False)

We can now re-read the data and begin to refine this to meet our needs:

In [48]: 
britburn = pd.read_excel("britburn.xls")

Now we want to compare the Britburn data to the Wikipedia data that we have already scraped and cleaned. We are only interested in retaining the data that relates directly to our Grammy winners and nominees. To compare the 'grammys' and 'britburn' dataframes, we can merge these, retaining all data from the 'grammys' dataframe. We will only keep data from the 'britburn' dataframe where the objects in 'Work' match the same variable in 'grammys':

In [51]: 
grammyswork = grammys.merge(britburn, how='left', on='Work')
grammyswork.info()

The information output above highlights a few key points:

    1. We now have 435 objects in the 'Work' variable. This could indicate that the same work has been performed by more than one artist.

      1. We have two variables named 'Artist': the original one contained within 'grammys' - 'Artist_x', and a new one called 'Artist_y'.

        1. The variables relating to chart position etc. appear to have a number of NaN values. This would suggest the the 'britburn' datafile does not contain all of the data we will need to perform our analysis.

Note, the Britburn dataset only covered the period up to 31 December 2000 and our Wikipedia data covered the Grammy awards up to and including 2015. It would be natural to expect some null values.

If we consider the first three rows, we can see that 'Volare' appears in the Britburn data three times, each recorded by a different artist. We are only concerned with the version recorded by Domenico Modugno.

Row 3 shows that 'Mack the Knife' has no matching record in the Britburn data. This seems strange given the popularity of this song during the 1960's. One limitation of merging dataframes is that the merge variable 'on', in this case we selected 'Work', needs to be identical in both dataframes. Looking down the list above, we can see that in row 90 Ray Charles' 1967 performance of "Here We Go Again" has led to a part match with his more modern duet with Norah Jones. We can also see that rows 14 and 45 have similar issues. We can drop these rows from our main dataframe and then consider the remainder of the responses. Note, as we drop row 14, we have to reduce the latter numbers accordingly. This is because if we were to then drop row 45, python will select what we currently know as row 46 and so on as it accommodates the rows that have been dropped.

In [61]: 
grammyswork.drop(grammyswork.index[[14]], inplace=True)
grammyswork.drop(grammyswork.index[[44]], inplace=True)
grammyswork.drop(grammyswork.index[[88]], inplace=True)

To obain the remainder of the chart data, we can attempt to scrape this from the "Official Charts" website. This website holds charts data as far back as the 1950's. If we look at the entry for "Grenade" by Bruno Mars, we can see that it is necessary to click on a button in order to obtain the historical data:

In [6]: 
HTML('<iframe src=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/grenade width=1050 height=500></iframe>')
Out[6]:

What we can do is put in place a loop that allows us to scrape the pages relating to our songs that have missing data. Firstly, we can create a new variable where we can save part of the url for each song:

In [80]:

chartmissing.head(2)

Then, we can define a function that replaces whitespace in our 'offchart' variable with %20, which is how words are separated in the urls for officialcharts.com:

In [82]: 
def perctwent(o):

     # Replace all runs of whitespace with a %20
     o = re.sub(r"\s+", '%20', o)

     return o

We can then apply this function to our objects:

In [83]: 
chartmissing['offchart'] = chartmissing['offchart'].apply(perctwent)
chartmissing.head(10)
Out[83]:

Then, we can create a csv file, then append our new part url to the base url for officialcharts.com. From there, we can then attempt to scrape the website. Firstly though, it would be advantageous to see if our urls are correct. We can judge this by response code:

In [84]: 
headers = { 'User-Agent' : 'Mozilla/5.0' }
testout = open("testoutcome.csv", "wb")
to1 = csv.writer(testout)
to1.writerow(['code', 'numb'])

test_list = []
for numb in chartmissing.offchart:
    address = ('http://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/ ' + numb)
    resp = requests.head(address, headers=headers)

    to1.writerow([resp.status_code, numb])
      
testout.close()

Using coding variations upon a theme would not allow the data inside the + button to be scraped. It appeared resistent to automated scraping.

Offical Charts also do not offer an API. Their data is monetised so it makes sense that barriers are put in place to prevent all but the most determined (and skilled) coders from scraping their site.

We also require song length data. This can usually be obtained from the infobox on the song's Wikipedia page, as seen below:

#Web Scraping - Back to Wikipedia

In [7]: 
HTML('<iframe src=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/What_a_Fool_Believes width=1050 height=500></iframe>')
Out[7]:

We could look to scrape the Wikipedia pages that relate to our songs with missing data.

Firstly, we can scrape the Wikipedia page that contains the table that summarises all of the award winners and nominees to see if the hyperlinks to each song are easily accessible:

In [91]: 
url = 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Record_of_the_Year'
lru = urllib2.urlopen(url).read()
gramurl = BeautifulSoup(lru,'html.parser')

for link in gramurl('a'):
       u = link.get('href')
       print u

The results show songs, artists and links to specific articles about particular award years. These are all jumbled up together and not easily copied, but do give us some clue as to Wikipedia's naming convention for urls/links.

Songs (or artists) generally have a prefix of '/wiki/', then the name with underscores instead of whitespace (e.g. '/wiki/Percy_Faith'). We can create a part link by inserting a new variable into the dataframe:

In [92]: 
grammysmain.insert(5, 'WikiLink', grammysmain.Work)
grammysmain.head()
Out[92]:
Year Work Artist Winner Year_Won WikiLink Year_First_Charts Wks_in_Chart Wks_in_Top40 Wks_in_Top10 Wks_Highest_Pos High_Pos Song_Length
0 1959 Nel Blu Dipinto Di Blu (Volare) Domenico Modugno 1 1959 Nel Blu Dipinto Di Blu (Volare) 1958 12 11 1 1 10 03 31
1 1960 Mack The Knife Bobby Darin 1 1960 Mack The Knife 1959 18 6 11 2 1 03 06
2 1961 Theme From A Summer Place Percy Faith 1 1961 Theme From A Summer Place 1960 31 22 7 1 2 02 17
3 1962 Moon River Henry Mancini 1 1962 Moon River 1961 3 - - 1 44 02 38
4 1963 I Left My Heart In San Francisco Tony Bennett 1 1963 I Left My Heart In San Francisco 1965 14 9 - 3 25 02 51

We can now define a function that allows us to replace the whitespace between each word in the song title with an underscore so as to conform with Wikipedia's naming convention:

In [93]: 
def undersc(o):

     o = re.sub(r"\s+", '_', o)

     return o

Then apply this to the new link we have created:

In [94]: 
grammysmain['WikiLink'] = grammysmain['WikiLink'].apply(undersc)
grammysmain.head(10)
Out[94]:
Year Work Artist Winner Year_Won WikiLink Year_First_Charts Wks_in_Chart Wks_in_Top40 Wks_in_Top10 Wks_Highest_Pos High_Pos Song_Length
0 1959 Nel Blu Dipinto Di Blu (Volare) Domenico Modugno 1 1959 Nel_Blu_Dipinto_Di_Blu_(Volare) 1958 12 11 1 1 10 03 31
1 1960 Mack The Knife Bobby Darin 1 1960 Mack_The_Knife 1959 18 6 11 2 1 03 06
2 1961 Theme From A Summer Place Percy Faith 1 1961 Theme_From_A_Summer_Place 1960 31 22 7 1 2 02 17
3 1962 Moon River Henry Mancini 1 1962 Moon_River 1961 3 - - 1 44 02 38
4 1963 I Left My Heart In San Francisco Tony Bennett 1 1963 I_Left_My_Heart_In_San_Francisco 1965 14 9 - 3 25 02 51
5 1964 Days Of Wine And Roses Henry Mancini 1 NaN Days_Of_Wine_And_Roses NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN
6 1965 The Girl From Ipanema Astrud Gilberto And Stan Getz 1 NaN The_Girl_From_Ipanema NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN
7 1966 A Taste Of Honey Herb Alpert And The Tijuana Brass 1 NaN A_Taste_Of_Honey NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN
8 1967 Strangers In The Night Frank Sinatra 1 1967 Strangers_In_The_Night 1966 20 19 8 3 1 02 37
9 1968 Up, Up And Away The 5th Dimension 1 NaN Up,_Up_And_Away NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN NaN

Now we can create a new dataframe that contains only that songs that do not have length data:

In [95]: 
nolength = grammysmain[(pd.isnull(grammysmain['Song_Length']))]
nolength.info()

<class 'pandas.core.frame.DataFrame'>
Int64Index: 149 entries, 5 to 284
Data columns (total 13 columns):
Year                 149 non-null int64
Work                 149 non-null object
Artist               149 non-null object
Winner               30 non-null float64
Year_Won             44 non-null float64
WikiLink             149 non-null object
Year_First_Charts    44 non-null float64
Wks_in_Chart         44 non-null float64
Wks_in_Top40         44 non-null object
Wks_in_Top10         44 non-null object
Wks_Highest_Pos      44 non-null object
High_Pos             44 non-null float64
Song_Length          0 non-null object
dtypes: float64(5), int64(1), object(7)
memory usage: 12.2+ KB

This shows that we have 149 null objects. We can now test our theory to see if our newly created links work.

Firstly, we can create a new csv file and write two variables that will a) record the code returned when we attempt to access our newly created url, and b) note the name of the song so we know which ones have worked and which have failed. We can then take the main Wikipedia url of 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/' and prefix it to our song titles which have underscores added, looping around until we reach the end of our "nolength" dataframe:

In [96]: 
testout = open("testoutcome.csv", "wb")
to1 = csv.writer(testout)
to1.writerow(['code', 'numb'])

test_list = []
for numb in nolength.WikiLink:
    address = ('http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/' + numb)
    resp = requests.head(address)

    to1.writerow([resp.status_code, numb])
      
testout.close()

We want to ensure that an attempt was made to access 149 urls:

In [97]: 
testoutcome = pd.read_csv('testoutcome.csv')
print testoutcome.count()
testoutcome.head()

code    149
numb    149
dtype: int64
Out[97]:
code numb
0 200 Days_Of_Wine_And_Roses
1 200 The_Girl_From_Ipanema
2 200 A_Taste_Of_Honey
3 200 Up,_Up_And_Away
4 200 This_Masquerade

Knowing that if we receive response code 200 then the url is correct, we can find how many of our urls are incorrect by looking at those with response codes other than 200:

In [98]: 
testoutcome = testoutcome[(testoutcome.code != 200)]
testoutcome
Out[98]:
code numb
39 404 Where_Have_All_The_Cowboys_Gone?
59 404 Fly_Me_To_The_Moon_Bossa_Nova
97 404 Something_To_Talk_About
99 404 If_I_Ever_Lose_My_Faith_In_You
119 404 Locked_Out_Of_Heaven
122 404 Wives_And_Lovers
135 404 Drops_Of_Jupiter_(Tell_Me)

Seven out of 149 isn't too bad. A quick search through our initial link scraping will reveal the correct formatting:

In [99]: 
url = 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Record_of_the_Year'
lru = urllib2.urlopen(url).read()
gramurl = BeautifulSoup(lru,'html.parser')

for link in gramurl('a'):
       u = link.get('href')
       print u

Recreate the "nolength" dataframe so it reflects the updated data:

In [101]: 
nolength = grammysmain[(pd.isnull(grammysmain['Song_Length']))]

Rerun our code to see if our urls are correct across the entire subset:

In [102]: 
testout = open("testoutcome.csv", "wb")
to1 = csv.writer(testout)
to1.writerow(['code', 'numb'])

test_list = []
for numb in nolength.WikiLink:
    address = ('http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/' + numb)
    resp = requests.head(address)

    to1.writerow([resp.status_code, numb])
      
testout.close()

As this looks to be successful, we can now try to scrape the pages and return the song lengths. As an example we can return the following data for "Put Your Records On":

In [105]: 
import requests

url = 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Put_Your_Records_On'
resp = requests.get(url, params={'action': 'raw'})
page = resp.text

for line in page.splitlines():
     if line.startswith('| Length'):
        length = line.partition('=')[-1].strip()
        break
 
print url, length

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Put_Your_Records_On 3:35

Regretfully, no matter how much I tried I was unable to resolve this issue. A search for other ways or methods of obtaining the both the song length and chart data was unsuccessful.

As we are already committed to obtaining the data in order to complete our dataset, it was decided to manually visit the website and collate the data in a CSV file (i.e. me, mouse clicks and a spreadsheet).

To do this, we can write the grammysmain dataframe to a csv file, manually update this with the new data, then read this back into the Notebook:

In [107]: 
grammysmain.to_csv("grammysmaintest.csv")
In [108]: 
grammysmain = pd.read_csv("grammysmainnew.csv")
grammysmain.head(5)

#Static Dataset - The Million Song Dataset

In [9]: 
HTML('<iframe src=http://labrosa.ee.columbia.edu/millionsong/ width=1050 height=500></iframe>')
Out[9]:

The Million Song Dataset is a collaboration between The Laboratory for the Recognition and Organization of Speech and Audio (LABROSA at Columbia University) and The EchoNest. Both parties apply machine learning to sound, in an attempt to interpret this in a way that makes sense of the data. The entire dataset is 280GB, however part of is is available in snapshot form.

In order to use The EchoNest API at latter stages, it is helpful to have both the Artist and Song ID's that relate to the EchoNest data. Part of this information is available from The Million Songs snapshot alluded to above.

We have downloaded the information and saved this, removing the sheets we do not require. The remainder of the data can now be read into our Notebook:

In [110]: 
labrosaart = pd.read_excel('labrosa_artist.xlsx', header=0)
labrosaart.head(5)
Out[110]:
echoART_ID Artist
0 AR002UA1187B9A637D The Bristols
1 AR003FB1187B994355 The Feds
2 AR006821187FB5192B Stephen Varcoe/Choir of King's College_ Cambri...
3 AR009211187B989185 Carroll Thompson
4 AR009SZ1187B9A73F4 Gorodisch

Above we have the name of the artist, along with their EchoNest ID. We can see below how many objects are contained in this dataset:

In [111]:

We can now merge this with our grammysmain dataframe and begin the process of matching ID's to Artists:

In [112]: 
gramlabart = grammysmain.merge(labrosaart, how='left', on='Artist')
gramlabart = pd.DataFrame(gramlabart)
sl = gramlabart.columns.tolist()
sl

We have generated the list of variables above. As our dataframe grows, the columns that we are constantly looking at sometimes are found to the right of the dataframe. This means we need to scroll across in our workbook. What we can do is rearrange the columns so "echoART_ID" is to the left, thus minimising the scrolling:

In [113]: 
sl = sl[-1:] + sl[:-1]
sl

We can see that Frank Sinatra has three artist ID's. In order to obtain further information (starting with the EchoNest ID) we can now refer to the EchoNest API.

#API - The EchoNest

In [10]: 
HTML('<iframe src=http://the.echonest.com/ width=1050 height=500></iframe>')
Out[10]:

"The Echo Nest was an audio fingerprinting service for developers and media companies. Based in Somerville, MA, the Echo Nest was spun-off from the MIT Media Lab to understand the audio and textual content of recorded music." [Source: Wikipedia] It has since been acquired by Spotify and offers a number of services to the music industry and developers, including music discovery and personalisation, remixing and dynamic music applications. They have a catalogue of over 30 million songs, allowing people like us the opportnity to analyse songs and look for patterns.

For Frank Sinatra, we can assess his three artist ID's below by using the EchoNest API to call the response directly as a check:

In [118]: 
import pyechonest as pt
from pyechonest import artist
from pyechonest import song, track
import pyechonest.config as config
import pyechonest.song as song


print pt.artist.Artist(id='ARTASUV1187B9A2B67')
print pt.artist.Artist(id='ARXUCPO12086C169A4')
print pt.artist.Artist(id='ARXWYGG12454A37EF1')

Frank Sinatra
Frank Sinatra & Antnio Carlos Jobim
Frank Sinatra

We can see that one of these relates to a collaboration with Antnio Carlos Jobim. For consistency, we will check to see which ID is returned first when searching by artist name as it is our understanding that the first response tends to contain the bulk of the data relating to the artist:

In [119]: 
fsin = artist.search(name='frank sinatra')
 
if fsin:
    nisf = fsin[0]
    print '%s (Echo Nest Artist ID: %s)' % (nisf.name, nisf.id)
else:
    print 'Who is this person?'

Frank Sinatra (Echo Nest Artist ID: ARTASUV1187B9A2B67)

As the Frank Sinatra rows with other ID's are essentially duplicates, we can set these objects to a random number (e.g. 9999999999) that allows for easy removal at latter stages.

In [120]: 
def func9(a9a):
    if a9a['echoART_ID'] == ('ARXWYGG12454A37EF1'):
        return 9999999999
    elif a9a['echoART_ID'] == ('ARXUCPO12086C169A4'):
        return 9999999999
    else:
        return a9a['echoART_ID']
    
gramlabart['echoART_ID'] = gramlabart.apply(func9, axis=1)

Now we can check for other duplicate rows. We can insert a column entitled "isdupe" then use a boolean to confirm if the row contains a duplicate Work:

In [121]: 
gramlabart.insert(3, 'isdupe', ' ')
gramlabart['isdupe'] = gramlabart.duplicated('Work')

Using a function, we can apply the same 9999999999 data to the ID column to replace the redundant ID's in respect of these artists:

In [125]: 
def func10(b9b):
    if b9b['echoART_ID'] == ('ARJ08091187FB5B079'):
        return 9999999999
    elif b9b['echoART_ID'] == ('ARNDBEM1187B9A2918'):
        return 9999999999
    elif b9b['echoART_ID'] == ('ARUDBB61187B9AEA91'):
        return 9999999999
    elif b9b['echoART_ID'] == ('ARWDNGQ12454A52AF1'):
        return 9999999999
    else:
        return b9b['echoART_ID']
    
gramlabart['echoART_ID'] = gramlabart.apply(func10, axis=1)

Then put these into a series of functions that allow us to call the EchoNest API and search for the Artist ID.

As I was unable to get a loop to work, I used a mailmerge in Microsoft Word to automate the generation of the lines of code below:

For some artists, especially for single duets or for songs that are sung by A but feature B, there is only an ID for the main singer or for each singer individually. In this case, we have taken the main singer or the first singer of the duet.

We can then take the information from our function above and re-run our code:

We can now create a new dataframe with just the three columns that we want. This allows us to then merge this information back into our working dataframe and not have to subsequently deal with a large number of duplicated columns and then having to delete them:

In [135]: 
igd2 = pd.DataFrame(igd1, columns=['echoART_ID', 'Work', 'Artist'])

By joining on two variables ('Work' and 'Artist') we remove the problem that occurs when joining solely on 'Work' - i.e. as 'Mack the Knife' has been nominated twice but sung by two different artists, we end up with two duplicate rows.

In [136]: 
gramig = gramlabart.merge(igd2, how='left', on=['Artist', 'Work'])

Now, we can define a function that either retains the ID gained from the Million Song Dataset, or if that column is null, takes the ID acquired from EchoNest:

In [139]: 
def func19(a19a):
    if pd.isnull(a19a['echoART_ID_x']):
        return a19a['echoART_ID_y']
    else:
        return a19a['echoART_ID_x']
    
gramig['echoART_ID_x'] = gramig.apply(func19, axis=1)

We can see that in some cases (e.g. duets where the artists came together for one or two songs) each individual artist has an ID, but not the duet. An example of this is Streisand and Diamond's rendition of "You Don't Bring Me Flowers". For consistency, in these instances we have used the first partner in the duet, or the main singer in a case where another artist is "featured".

We can see that one of our songs was not able to be found. This was Henry Mancini's "A Time For Us". An internet search shows that this was also known as The Love Theme From Romeo and Juliet, although the Grammy was awarded to "A Time For Us":

In [154]: 
misong = song.search(artist="mancini", title="romeo and", results=5, start=0)
if misong:
    for ax in misong:
       print '"%s": "%s",' % (ax.title, ax.id) 
       print '"%s": "%s",' % (ax.artist_name, ax.artist_id) 
else:
    print 'No songs found.'
print ''

We have two missing ID's. These relate to "Mack The Knife", which was recorded by both Bobby Darin and Ella Fitzgerald. If we were to save the work name and ID into a dictionary then only the latter would be mapped. We can now map this separately. Firstly, we need to find the song id for each rendition:

In [158]: 
sid = song.search(title='Mack The Knife', artist_id="ARD0FN11187B9B25CD", results=1)
if sid:
    for sidy in sid:
        print '"%s": "%s",' % (sidy.title, sidy.id)
        print '"%s", "%s"' % (sidy.artist_name, sidy.artist_id)
        print ''
else:
        print 'Mack The Knife' 
        
sid = song.search(title='Mack The Knife', artist_id="ARIJE1A1187B9A458D", results=1)
if sid:
    for sidy in sid:
        print '"%s": "%s",' % (sidy.title, sidy.id)
        print '"%s", "%s"' % (sidy.artist_name, sidy.artist_id)
else:
        print 'Mack The Knife'

We then define a function then apply this to our dataframe, inserting the missing Song ID's:

In [160]: 
def func07(b07b):
    if b07b['echoART_ID'] == "ARD0FN11187B9B25CD":
        return "SOHSRHM13672AEEA4A"
    elif b07b['echoART_ID'] == "ARIJE1A1187B9A458D":
        return "SODECWR144C9F84C9E"
    else:
        return b07b['echo_SONGID']
    
gramlabsong['echo_SONGID'] = gramlabsong.apply(func07, axis=1)

We can see that a number of songs didn't chart at all. The maximum number of weeks in the chart so far has been 83 (note, this is consecutive - as soon as the song dropped out of the charts then counting stopped for the purposes of this analysis. There were examples of songs having come back into the charts twenty years later, so for consistency the rule of "out of the charts, counting stops" was applied. Otherwise, newer songs would be prejudiced by simply being newer, not having had the opportunity for the Work to be re-released).

We can also see that a number of our numeric variables are saved as objects. This is because we have a mix of scraped data, where nil entries were saved as "-", and manual data where nil entries were saved as "0". We can change this by replacing the "-" with a "0" for consistency and then looking at the values to ensure this has occurred:

In [166]: 
grammysmain['Wks_in_Top40'] = grammysmain['Wks_in_Top40'].replace("-", 0)
grammysmain['Wks_in_Top10'] = grammysmain['Wks_in_Top10'].replace("-", 0)
grammysmain['Wks_Highest_Pos'] = grammysmain['Wks_Highest_Pos'].replace("-", 0)
grammysmain.describe()

The first two digits relate to minutes, with the second two relating to seconds. We can add two new columns, then map the minutes to one and the seconds to another:

In [171]: 
grammysmain['song_mins'] = ''
grammysmain['song_secs'] = ''
In [172]: 
grammysmain['song_mins'] = grammysmain['Song_Length'].str.split(' ').str[0]
grammysmain['song_secs'] = grammysmain['Song_Length'].str.split(' ').str[1]
grammysmain.info()

Interestingly, the average song length is 227 seconds (or 3 min 47 seconds). There have been a number of discussions about the "perfect" length for a pop song (apparently it is 2 minutes 42 seconds / or under 3 minutes https://www.google.co.nz/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&ion=1&espv=2&ie=UTF-8#q=perfect%20song%20length). We can see that two of our songs (both from the 1960's) are 2 minutes and 1 second long, with the longest being nearly 6 & 1/2 minutes long.

We can now use the EchoNest API to obtain further data about each song. Applying a combination of human assessment and maching learning, EchoNest have made available song data that explains energy, beats per minute, time signature and other interesting facts. An example of this in relation to one song can be found below:

In [178]: 
song_ids = grammysmain['echo_SONGID'].tolist()
song_ids1 = song_ids[0:10]
songs = song.profile(ids=song_ids1, buckets=['audio_summary'])
songs[1].audio_summary

We can use our API key to obtain some of this data and append it to our dataframe. Echonest allow a user to call 10 song ID's at a time, so we can (using a Word mailmerge again) create code that obtains the data we are seeking for each of our songs:

In [179]: 
sing_ids = grammysmain['echo_SONGID'].tolist()

songs = song.profile(ids=sing_ids[0:10], buckets=['audio_summary'])
for sing in songs:
    print "'%s': ""[%s, " "%s, " "%s, " "%s, " "%s, " "%s, " "%s]," % (sing.id, sing.audio_summary['danceability'], sing.audio_summary['energy'], sing.audio_summary['loudness'], sing.audio_summary['speechiness'], sing.audio_summary['tempo'], sing.audio_summary['time_signature'], sing.audio_summary['valence'])

We can see that there is a range of energy responses - a reading of 1 indicates a high energy song, although most appear to be clustered around the 0.33-0.68 region.

Speechiness has been added as a safeguard to ensure that we haven't accidentally obtained data relating to an artist talking about their song.

Most songs appear to be in 4/4 time.

There is a wide range; interestingly, the lower energy songs tend to be older than the higher energy songs. Until we perform more in depth analysis it is difficult to to ascertain if this is an anomaly or if energy has changed over time.

Loudness is very topical. There have been discussions regarding sound engineering and whether a song's loudness quotient has increased over the years. One argument is that the louder the song the more attention it gets. Others argue that an increase in loudness has the effect of reducing quality of sound and the listener can miss the nuances. We can see that our older songs are likely to be at the quieter end of the scale than our more modern songs.

The time signature ranges from 3 to 7 indicating time signatures of 3/4, to 7/4. A value of -1 may indicate no time signature, while a value of 1 indicates a rather complex or changing time signature (or one that has not been able to be easily assessed). http://developer.echonest.com/docs/v4/_static/AnalyzeDocumentation.pdf

We can see that four of our songs have time signatures in exess of 4/4, with only 19 being less than 3/4. The Beatles "Yesterday" has a signature of 1 - the sheet music shows a 4/4 time, however this discussion - http://ask.metafilter.com/194911/Error-in-This-is-your-brain-on-music-regarding-Yesterday - could explain some of the complexity in the music that has led to the song not being easily classified during the machine learning process.

#Exploratory Data Analysis - Calculation of Artist Name & Song Title Data

We can now look at how many characters (including spaces) each Work has in its title by using a length (len) function, then applying this to the objects in the Work variable:

In [198]: 
grammysmain.insert(4, 'Work_chars', ' ')
def func49(a49a):
    for a in a49a:
        return len(a49a['Work'])
    else:
        return None
    
grammysmain['Work_chars'] = grammysmain.apply(func49, axis=1)

Whilst it is preferable to retain the "NaN" values, when using mysql.connector we can experience issues with inserting these values into a MySQL database. "NaN" values are unreadable and cause an error. To minimise any issues we can convert these to "0". This preserves the variable as an integer or float:

In [205]: 
grammysmain['Winner'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

We can start by creating a table that contains the Work (song) data. We will call this 'work' and then confirm the variable headings:

In [211]: 
TABLES = {}
TABLES['works'] = (
    "CREATE TABLE `works` ("
    "  `echo_SONGID` varchar(20) NOT NULL,"
    "  `year` int(4) NOT NULL,"
    "  `winner` int(5),"
    "  `work` varchar(150) NOT NULL,"
    "  `work_chars` int(3) NOT NULL,"
    "  `work_words` int(2) NOT NULL,"
    "  PRIMARY KEY `echo_SONGID` (`echo_SONGID`)"
    ") ENGINE=InnoDB")

We then execute the table construction so it is persisted (saved) into the MySQL database 'grammy':

In [214]: 
from StringIO import StringIO
from __future__ import print_function
from mysql.connector import errorcode

for name, ddl in TABLES.iteritems():
    try:
        print("Creating table {}: ".format(name), end='')
        cursor.execute(ddl)
    except mysql.connector.Error as err:
        if err.errno == errorcode.ER_TABLE_EXISTS_ERROR:
            print("already exists in database.")
        else:
            print(err.msg)
    else:
        print("OK")

Creating table works: OK

We can now begin the process of constructing iterations that allow us to automatically insert our cleaned data into the MySQL database tables.

Firstly, can generate a list of the keys and use these in our for loop:

In [215]: 
grammysmain.keys()

Firstly we create the for loop. We require it to iterate through each of the rows in grammysmain, taking all of the objects within each selected variable. We can print the outcome to check that the data is as we require it. Then, we can combine these parts together to create our loop, finishing this with an instruction to the cursor to place the data into our new SQL table:

In [216]: 
for index, row in grammysmain.iterrows():
    work_entry = (row['echo_SONGID'], row['Year'], row['Winner'], row['Work'], row['Work_chars'], row['Work_words'])   
    add_work_entry = """  
                                INSERT INTO works 
                                (echo_SONGID, year, winner, work, work_chars, work_words) 
                                VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s)
                     """
    cursor.execute(add_work_entry, work_entry)
    cnct.commit()

We can now create tables for the remainder of our data, splitting the data contained within 'grammysmain' into tables as appropriate:

In [217]: 
TABLESA = {}
TABLESA['artists'] = (
    "CREATE TABLE `artists` ("
    "  `echo_SONGID` varchar(20) NOT NULL,"
    "  `echoART_ID` varchar(20) NOT NULL,"
    "  `artist` varchar(150) NOT NULL,"
    "  `artist_chars` int(3) NOT NULL,"
    "  `artist_words` int(2) NOT NULL,"
    "  PRIMARY KEY `echo_SONGID` (`echo_SONGID`), KEY `artists` (`echo_SONGID`),"
    "  CONSTRAINT FOREIGN KEY (`echo_SONGID`) REFERENCES `works` (`echo_SONGID`) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE"
    ") ENGINE=InnoDB")

TABLESA['charts'] = (
    "CREATE TABLE `charts` ("
    "  `echo_SONGID` varchar(20) NOT NULL,"
    "  `wks_in_chart` int(3),"
    "  `wks_in_top40` int(3),"
    "  `wks_in_top10` int(3),"
    "  `wks_highest_pos` int(3),"
    "  `high_pos` int(3),"
    "  PRIMARY KEY `echo_SONGID` (`echo_SONGID`), KEY `charts` (`echo_SONGID`),"
    "  CONSTRAINT FOREIGN KEY (`echo_SONGID`) REFERENCES `works` (`echo_SONGID`) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE"
    ") ENGINE=InnoDB")

TABLESA['songs'] = (
    "CREATE TABLE `songs` ("
    "  `echo_SONGID` varchar(20) NOT NULL,"
    "  `song_length` int(5) NOT NULL,"
    "  `danceability` float(8) NOT NULL,"
    "  `energy` float(8) NOT NULL,"
    "  `loudness` float(8) NOT NULL,"
    "  `tempo` float(8) NOT NULL,"
    "  `time_signature` float(8) NOT NULL,"
    "  `valence` float(8) NOT NULL,"
    "  PRIMARY KEY `echo_SONGID` (`echo_SONGID`), KEY `songs` (`echo_SONGID`),"
    "  CONSTRAINT FOREIGN KEY (`echo_SONGID`) REFERENCES `works` (`echo_SONGID`) ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE"
    ") ENGINE=InnoDB")

for index, row in grammysmain.iterrows():
    artist_entry = (row['echo_SONGID'], row['echoART_ID'], row['Artist'], row['Artist_chars'], row['Artist_words'])   
    add_artist_entry = """  
                                INSERT INTO artists 
                                (echo_SONGID, echoART_ID, artist, artist_chars, artist_words) 
                                VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s, %s)
                     """
    cursor.execute(add_artist_entry, artist_entry)
    cnct.commit()
    
for index, row in grammysmain.iterrows():
    charts_entry = (row['echo_SONGID'], row['Wks_in_Chart'], row['Wks_in_Top40'], row['Wks_in_Top10'], row['Wks_Highest_Pos'], row['High_Pos'])   
    add_charts_entry = """  
                                INSERT INTO charts 
                                (echo_SONGID, wks_in_chart, wks_in_top40, wks_in_top10, wks_highest_pos, high_pos) 
                                VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s)
                     """
    cursor.execute(add_charts_entry, charts_entry)
    cnct.commit()
  
for index, row in grammysmain.iterrows():
    songs_entry = (row['echo_SONGID'], row['Song_Length'], row['Danceability'], row['Energy'], row['Loudness'], row['Tempo'], row['Time_Signature'], row['Valence'])   
    add_songs_entry = """  
                                INSERT INTO songs 
                                (echo_SONGID, song_length, danceability, energy, loudness, tempo, time_signature, valence) 
                                VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s, %s)
                     """
    cursor.execute(add_songs_entry, songs_entry)
    cnct.commit()

#MySQL - Schema

There are 285 individual echoART SONG ID's and the associated works. Each Work has one artist, but one artist can have more than one work. This gives us the following Schema:

In [221]: 
from IPython.display import Image
Image(filename='Schema.png')
Out[221]:

#5. Cleaned Data - Explanatory Notes

Below are explanatory notes that relate to each table in our schema:

WORKS:

    1. echo_SONGID - This is the EchoNest unique ID that identifies the nominated record.

      1. year - The year that the record was nominated for the Grammy.

        1. winner - Indicates if the record won or not - 1 indicates winner, 0 indicates not the winner.

          1. work - The name of the nominated record (i.e. song title).

            1. work_chars - The number of characters - including white spaces and special characters - in the name of the nominated work.

              1. work_words - The number of words - excluding white spaces in between words - in the name of the nominated work.

ARTISTS:

    1. echo_SONGID - This is the EchoNest unique ID that identifies the nominated record.

      1. echoART_ID - This is the EchoNest unique ID that identifies the artist/s associated with the nominated record.

        1. artist - The name of the artist associated with the nominated record.

          1. artist_chars - The number of characters - including white spaces and special characters - in the name of the artist associated with the nominated work.

            1. artist_words - The number of words - excluding white spaces in between words - in the name of the artist associated with the nominated work.

CHARTS:

    1. echo_SONGID - This is the EchoNest unique ID that identifies the nominated record.

      1. wks_in_chart- How many weeks in total the record spent in the UK charts - i.e. Top 100 - from date of first entry until date of first exit. For consistency, once the record dropped out of the charts any further re-entries were not considered.

        1. wks_in_top40- How many weeks in total the record spent in the Top 40 in the UK charts.

          1. wks_in_top10- How many weeks in total the record spent in the Top 10 in the UK charts.

            1. wks_highest_pos- The number of total weeks that the record spent in the highest position in the UK charts that it attained. Note: these may not be consecutive weeks.

              1. high_pos- The highest position in the UK charts that the record attained.

Note: UK chart data was chosen as this reflects actual sales (including digital), not radio or television airtime.

SONGS:

    1. echo_SONGID - This is the EchoNest unique ID that identifies the nominated record.

      1. song_length - The length of the record in seconds.

        1. danceability - The EchoNest danceability rating, defined as how easily a person could dance to a song. This is rated over the course of the entire song, using a number of different features as part of the calcuation (beat strength, tempo stability, dynamic range, overall tempo etc.). 0 equates to low danceability, 1 to maximum.

          1. energy - The EchoNest energy rating, or how energetic the song is. This is rated over the course of the entire song, using a number of different features as part of the calcuation (beat strength, tempo stability, dynamic range, overall tempo etc.) 0 equates to low energy, 1 to maximum.

            1. loudness - The EchoNest loudness calculation. This is "the overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values in the Analyzer are averaged across an entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of segments and tracks. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude)."

              1. tempo - The EchoNest tempo calculation, being "the overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). In musical terminology, tempo is the speed or pace of a given piece and derives directly from the average beat duration." The lower the figure the lower the tempo.

                1. time_signature - The EchoNest time signature calculation; an estimated overall time signature of a track. The time signature (meter) is a notational convention to specify how many beats are in each bar (or measure)." These range from 3/4 to 7/8. -1 indicates dirty data. 1 indicates a difficult to classify track.

                  1. valence - The EchoNest valence calculation; this is a perceived happiness calculation and is based on a number of features. 0 equates to low valence, 1 to maximum.

Further information about The EchoNest attributes can be found here: http://developer.echonest.com/docs/v4/_static/AnalyzeDocumentation.pdf

Please now open Part 2 for analysis and answers to our questions.
